KAYPRO 4

•	What year was it made? 
1984

•	What operating system does it run?
Kaypro 2.2

•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). 
Then: $1800.00
Now: $299.00 on EBAY -- there are multiple options for diskets, but I only found 1 for an actual computer

•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
According to the Wikipedia article, "Arthur C. Clarke used a Kaypro II to write and collaboratively edit (via modem from Sri Lanka) his 1982 novel 2010: Odyssey Two." 

So the Kaypro will always have that. At the time of its release, it was mostly praised for its durability. It went through rapid transformations to try to keep up with 

competitors, even if their hardware components remained almost identical to the last. It was bankrupted by the 1990s, but Microsoft did briefly try to revive it and 

failed. 


Turn it on (you must figure out how). Start WordStar (you must figure out how). Try typing a simple document, experimenting with some commands based on the keyboard 

template. (You don’t need to save your document.)

~#turn it on by a switch on the back of the computer
~#I put the disket for WordStar in, typed, but could not get any of the commands to work for me
~#this was the most frustrating of all the computers to work with.


