VECTREX

•	What year was it made?
1982

•	What operating system does it run? 
MineStorm is directly on the computer, but it runs cartridges by way of a Motorola 68A09 @ 1.5 MHz

•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
Then: $199; $470-adjusted for inflation
Now: there is a model on ebay for $422 and another for $550
 
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Vectrex is an entertainment system. It is designed for people's amusement and leisure time. If you have the free time to spend on games and have no need for a 

system with professional options, it is a good fit. Otherwise, the system could not be used for anything else.


Turn it on (you must figure out how). Play MineStorm. Try another cartridge. Why do you think the designer’s would have opted for the “vector” graphics?
~#took me the longest to figure out how to turn this one on, the fact that it is also the volume control/a turn knob made it a little tricky
~#MineStorm was fun, but I found navigating hard, so I just spun the spaceship around and shot randomly
~#I tried *Fortress of Norzoid*, but it wouldn't load
~#I could not figure out *Heads Up Soccer,* though I did manage to save a goal at one point
~#I found the graphics very simplistic, which means they were easy to replicate... the games all looke similar to each other... and mass production general means more 

money because people go out to buy more games, but the Wikipedia article says there was a video game crash the year after this was released and Vectrex was actually a 

failure

